    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#ferri1923"/>, p. 8, n. <citedRange>7e</citedRange>, fig. 8</bibl>, and 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#oliverioDAI1"/>, pp. 166-167, n. <citedRange>48</citedRange>, tab. XXVII, figs. 52-53</bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>9.350</citedRange></bibl>; 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#jmr1976"/>, n. <citedRange>1</citedRange></bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>27.1125bis</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>033300</citedRange></bibl>. 
                    Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#chamoux1998"/><citedRange/></bibl>, and 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#callot1999"/>, pp. 85-86, n. <citedRange>41</citedRange></bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>48.2047</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#cdl2000"/>, p. <citedRange>227</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" atLeast="4" atMost="5" unit="character"/><persName type="divine" ref="#Kallikrateia"><name nymRef="#Καλλικράτεια">Καλλικρατείας</name></persName>.
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p><app loc="1"><note>no gap mentioned by others at the beginning</note></app></p>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" atLeast="4" atMost="5" unit="character"/> de Kallikrateia.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" atLeast="4" atMost="5" unit="character"/> of Kallikrateia.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p><gap reason="lost" atLeast="4" atMost="5" unit="character"/> di Kallikrateia.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>The preserved name does not begin at the left end of the space available, where rests of illegible letters seem to exist under later graffiti;
                 however there is not enough space for a word like <foreign xml:lang="grc">ἐσχάρα</foreign>. Might it be some form of <foreign xml:lang="grc">ἱαρός</foreign>?</p>
                <p>The date of the inscription, erroneously given as first century BC in <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>9.350</citedRange></bibl>, was said
                    «<foreign xml:lang="it">buona epoca</foreign>» by <bibl><ptr target="#oliverioDAI1"/>, pp. 166-167, n. <citedRange>48</citedRange></bibl> and «probably early third century BC»
                    by <bibl><ptr target="#jmr1976"/>, n. <citedRange>1</citedRange></bibl>. But both epsilon and rho at least belong to an older period, even older than
                    the end of the fourth century (so <bibl><ptr target="#callot1999"/>, pp. <citedRange>85-86</citedRange>, n. <citedRange>41</citedRange></bibl> and
                    <bibl><ptr target="#cdl2000"/>, p. <citedRange>227</citedRange></bibl>).</p>
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#chamoux1998"/></bibl> suggested that the name was an epithet or a cult-name of Artemis, as a protector of the port. 
                    For other deities honoured on the spot, see <bibl><ptr target="#cdl2012a"/>, pp. <citedRange>230-231</citedRange></bibl> and <ref type="inscription" source="#GVCyr2">GVCyr052</ref>.</p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
